		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">In general relativity, Einstein's theory of gravity, one cannot readily define energy and momentum for gravitational fields, which makes interpretation difficult. This happens because a basic physical principle of the theory, the principle of equivalence, implies that there cannot be a purely local definition of energy. In astrophysical situations involving sources of radiation, they are often treated as isolated bodies, and with appropriate boundary conditions, energy and momentum are then well-defined. A number of other conserved quantities of physical interest could be defined under certain conditions. This project aims to investigate some aspects of one of those conditions, the existence of  conformal Killing-Yano tensors .A second area we would aim to work on is the construction of models of a system of two black holes encountering one another. The difficulty we wish to overcome is that it is hard to define a starting point for the evolution of such a system that contains only a minimal amount of incoming radiation, so that all the radiation measured later is due to the encounter itself.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
